efaf8426-dcad-4752-b5a5-5c37810b77cc.2909fdf6-8d85-4c1a-9b0e-2cf03a1ba7f8.transition.description=Iterator operation failed efaf8426-dcad-4752-b5a5-5c37810b77cc.3a59706c-3f19-4e1e-9a31-cf763ea21122.transition.description=Write Completed efaf8426-dcad-4752-b5a5-5c37810b77cc.49ea0a65-afa0-4d80-967f-144942ddfb50.description=
Writes the data from "contents" input to the requested file. The operation can be used to overwrite existing content of the file,  append extra lines to it or even create a new file.

Input Parameters\:
file                - Full path to file (can be a UNC path, will attempt to create directory structure). If the file does not exist it is created first.
contents        - The contents to write to the file. Contents can have a new line delimiter which is also given as input to the operation, but it is optional. Example\: "This is line no. 01\nThis is line no. 2\n" where \n is the delimiter.
user              - Username to use for thread impersonation on the RAS host for this operation.
password      - Password for the user.
delimiter       - Specifies the newline delimiter (\n, \r\n, etc) that is used for the "contents" input.
overwrite      - Specifies whether to overwrite the file or append to it. By default, the used value is true. Accepted values\: true, false or the empty string. If this is left empty, the file will be overwritten.
characterSet - The character encoding used to write to the file. The default is UTF-8. Example values\: windows-1252, UTF-16, UTF-16BE,  ISO-8859-1, US-ASCII, Shift_JIS etc.

Responses\:
success - The contents were written to the file.
failure - The operation did not succeed in writing the contents to file.

Compares two strings, returning a true response if and only if they contain the same sequence of characters. A null string is considered to be equal to an empty string.

Inputs\:
    string1 - The first string. 
Default value\: "" (empty)
    string2 - The second string.
Default value\: "" (empty)
    ignoreCase - If set to 'true', then the comparison ignores case considerations. The two strings are considered equal ignoring case if they are of the same length and corresponding characters in the two strings are equal ignoring case. If set to any value other than 'true', then the strings must match exactly to be considered equal.

Responses\:
    true - If the two strings are equal.
    false - If the two strings are not equal.
efaf8426-dcad-4752-b5a5-5c37810b77cc.bb4887f8-2695-41ef-85e1-1178e2a2cfd9.transition.description=OO System Error efaf8426-dcad-4752-b5a5-5c37810b77cc.c4b7e7e9-66c4-4c92-8dc9-b9c07d8d2737.description=
This operation loops as many times as specified in the "count" input, counting from "1" to a greater number, incrementing it by "1" at each iteration.

Inputs\:
    count - The number of loops to complete.
Valid values\: from 1 to 9223372036854775807
    reset - Specifies whether the counter restarts counting from "1".
Valid values\: true, false
Default value\: false
    to - The number to count to. It will take the value of the "count" input field. 
    from - The number to start counting at. For this operation, it is customized to "1".
    incrementBy - The number to increment by while counting. For this operation, it is customized to "1".

Results\:
    resultString – This is the primary output. It contains the value of the number that was just counted.

Responses\:
    has more – The counting process is not complete. One or more iterations are pending.
    no more – The counting process is complete.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.

Note\:
1. It is recommended that you do not change the values of the "to", "from" or "incrementBy" input fields.
2. The "from", "to" and "incrementBy" inputs are customized for this operation. Even though you can also customize them, if you need to specify the loop range borders and the increment value, use the "Counter" operation.

Examples\:
1. For a loop with 20 iterations, the following values should be provided for the input fields\:
    count\: 20
    reset\: false (this field can also be left blank, as "false" is the default value)
2. For an infinite loop, the value of "count" should be at least "1" and the value of "reset" should be "true".

efaf8426-dcad-4752-b5a5-5c37810b77cc.description=Create Log subflow will create a line in the Log file efaf8426-dcad-4752-b5a5-5c37810b77cc.e3a6c55f-8602-47fb-a892-3d2fbc8c5ac9.transition.description=Error Domain is Blank? efaf8426-dcad-4752-b5a5-5c37810b77cc.e6934baa-a4e3-4553-ad27-3fb20e58aa4d.description=
Check the current date and time, and returns a java DateAndTime formatted string of it. If locale is specified, it will return the date and time string based on the locale.Otherwise, default locale will be used.

Inputs\:
    localeLang - The locale language for date and time string. 
Examples\:  en, ja, unix.
    localeCountry - The locale country for date and time string. For example, US or JP. If localeLang is not specified, this input will be ingored.

Result\:
    Current date and time.

Responses\:
    success - Date/time retrieved successfully.   
    failure - Date/time could not be retrieved.

Notes.
    1. If localeLang is 'unix' the localeCountry input is ignored and the result will be the current UNIX timestamp.
efaf8426-dcad-4752-b5a5-5c37810b77cc.e6e198b7-2d4d-46d0-9051-e193af0d9233.description=
This operation iterates through a list of values. It is not recommended to modify the value of the "list" and "separator" inputs during the iteration process.

Inputs\:
    list - The list to iterate through.
    separator - A delimiter separating the list elements.
Default value\: ‘,’ (comma) 

Results\:
    resultString - The current list element (if the response is "has more").

Responses\:
    has more - Another value was found in the list and it has been returned.
    no more - The iterator has gone through the entire list. This response is returned once per list iteration.  A subsequent call to the List iterator operation restarts the list iteration process.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.

Note\:
   The position of the iterator in the list is tracked by each step's unique identifier. Therefore, you can simultaneously iterate through the same list from multiple steps.
